1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,850
INSTRUCTOR: So let's begin with
the first part of the lecture.

2
00:00:04,850 --> 00:00:09,320
To illustrate the methodology,
we will use a clinical example.

3
00:00:09,320 --> 00:00:11,540
The efficacy of
adjuvant imatinib

4
00:00:11,540 --> 00:00:15,140
for patients with localized
GIST was established

5
00:00:15,140 --> 00:00:18,020
in the first imatinib
versus placebo trial, which

6
00:00:18,020 --> 00:00:21,140
used broad inclusion criteria.

7
00:00:21,140 --> 00:00:23,930
That means the trial
included patients

8
00:00:23,930 --> 00:00:26,790
with even relatively
low risk of recurrence,

9
00:00:26,790 --> 00:00:30,650
the outcome imatinib
was designed to prevent.

10
00:00:30,650 --> 00:00:34,190
The trial showed a clear benefit
of treating resected GIST

11
00:00:34,190 --> 00:00:36,620
patients with imatinib.

12
00:00:36,620 --> 00:00:40,670
As a result, current selection
guidelines are liberal.

13
00:00:40,670 --> 00:00:44,070
Many patients, including
those with intermediate risk,

14
00:00:44,070 --> 00:00:46,250
receive treatment.

15
00:00:46,250 --> 00:00:49,130
This likely leads
to overtreatment.

16
00:00:49,130 --> 00:00:52,700
However, conducting a new
placebo-controlled RCT

17
00:00:52,700 --> 00:00:56,430
in lower-risk patients
is no longer ethical,

18
00:00:56,430 --> 00:00:59,610
as that would mean
withholding an established,

19
00:00:59,610 --> 00:01:02,810
effective treatment from
half of the participants.

20
00:01:02,810 --> 00:01:07,140
If we are wrong and imatinib is
still needed for some of them,

21
00:01:07,140 --> 00:01:09,500
we could be exposing
those patients

22
00:01:09,500 --> 00:01:11,610
to avoidable recurrence.

23
00:01:11,610 --> 00:01:15,200
This kind of experiment
would be unethical.

24
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:19,590
And, indeed, 25 years after
the original imatinib trial,

25
00:01:19,590 --> 00:01:23,750
no second placebo arm
study has been done.

26
00:01:23,750 --> 00:01:26,300
So the question
remains, How can we

27
00:01:26,300 --> 00:01:31,430
identify patients who do
not need adjuvant imatinib?

28
00:01:31,430 --> 00:01:36,200
What we will discuss here is
how to transform real-world data

29
00:01:36,200 --> 00:01:39,860
to make it suitable for
identifying patients who do not

30
00:01:39,860 --> 00:01:43,100
need adjuvant imatinib.

31
00:01:43,100 --> 00:01:46,050
Let's start with the top
left Kaplan-Meier plot,

32
00:01:46,050 --> 00:01:48,200
which you have already seen.

33
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:50,660
It shows the
recurrence-free survival

34
00:01:50,660 --> 00:01:53,360
of patients with
resected GIST based

35
00:01:53,360 --> 00:01:56,300
on whether they
received imatinib.

36
00:01:56,300 --> 00:01:59,090
Counterintuitively, patients
who received imatinib

37
00:01:59,090 --> 00:02:00,710
appear to do worse.

38
00:02:00,710 --> 00:02:04,440
That's a classic example of
confounding by indication.

39
00:02:04,440 --> 00:02:07,970
Those patients were more likely
to be treated because they had

40
00:02:07,970 --> 00:02:11,531
worse prognosis to begin with.

41
00:02:11,531 --> 00:02:15,230
To the right of this plot, I've
included the Kaplan-Meier curve

42
00:02:15,230 --> 00:02:20,120
from the original RCT comparing
imatinib versus placebo.

43
00:02:20,120 --> 00:02:23,810
As you can see, imatinib,
the curve with a solid line,

44
00:02:23,810 --> 00:02:25,230
was highly effective.

45
00:02:25,230 --> 00:02:27,720
It cut the recurrence
risk dramatically,

46
00:02:27,720 --> 00:02:30,110
at least for the
first three years.

47
00:02:30,110 --> 00:02:33,350
This is what the real-world
Kaplan-Meier curve

48
00:02:33,350 --> 00:02:38,300
should look like if
confounding were removed.

49
00:02:38,300 --> 00:02:41,450
Now look at the
bottom left panel.

50
00:02:41,450 --> 00:02:44,960
Here, we show the distribution
of baseline recurrence

51
00:02:44,960 --> 00:02:49,550
risk across our original
real-world cohort.

52
00:02:49,550 --> 00:02:52,130
Baseline risk refers to
the risk of recurrence

53
00:02:52,130 --> 00:02:54,740
if no treatment is given.

54
00:02:54,740 --> 00:02:57,950
To estimate this, we trained
the prognostic model only

55
00:02:57,950 --> 00:03:02,310
on untreated patients and then
applied it to both groups,

56
00:03:02,310 --> 00:03:04,620
including patients
treated with imatinib,

57
00:03:04,620 --> 00:03:09,020
to estimate their
counterfactual baseline risk.

58
00:03:09,020 --> 00:03:11,820
This is a classic
counterfactual approach.

59
00:03:11,820 --> 00:03:17,060
We ask, What would have happened
if this treated patient had not

60
00:03:17,060 --> 00:03:19,160
been treated?

61
00:03:19,160 --> 00:03:21,240
Focus on the bar heights.

62
00:03:21,240 --> 00:03:24,560
You will see that patients
who received imatinib

63
00:03:24,560 --> 00:03:27,630
tend to fall into
higher-risk categories,

64
00:03:27,630 --> 00:03:32,160
while those who didn't fall
into lower-risk categories.

65
00:03:32,160 --> 00:03:33,680
This makes sense.

66
00:03:33,680 --> 00:03:38,390
Clinicians base their treatment
decisions on baseline risk.

67
00:03:38,390 --> 00:03:40,340
We still have many
high-risk patients

68
00:03:40,340 --> 00:03:41,820
who didn't receive imatinib.

69
00:03:41,820 --> 00:03:45,320
This may be from the
preimatinib era or patients

70
00:03:45,320 --> 00:03:48,140
who declined treatment.

71
00:03:48,140 --> 00:03:51,050
This is an example of
observed confounding,

72
00:03:51,050 --> 00:03:53,600
as we were able to
measure it by training

73
00:03:53,600 --> 00:03:56,060
the counterfactual
baseline risk model using

74
00:03:56,060 --> 00:03:59,270
known prognostic variables.

75
00:03:59,270 --> 00:04:02,220
To address this
observed confounding,

76
00:04:02,220 --> 00:04:05,090
we apply prognostic matching.

77
00:04:05,090 --> 00:04:08,870
This isn't ordinary matching
on single variables.

78
00:04:08,870 --> 00:04:13,310
Instead, we match patients
within groups that share

79
00:04:13,310 --> 00:04:16,040
a similar baseline
prognosis estimated

80
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:18,260
from the counterfactual model.

81
00:04:18,260 --> 00:04:22,670
This safeguard ensures we
are matching only patients

82
00:04:22,670 --> 00:04:28,010
with similar expected outcomes
had they not been treated.

83
00:04:28,010 --> 00:04:30,410
The matching
optimization algorithm

84
00:04:30,410 --> 00:04:35,120
is shown below the
RCT Kaplan-Meier plot.

85
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:38,600
Now look at the
bottom right panel.

86
00:04:38,600 --> 00:04:41,840
After matching, the treated
and untreated patients

87
00:04:41,840 --> 00:04:45,890
are well balanced across
all baseline risk buckets.

88
00:04:45,890 --> 00:04:50,510
This is a visual check
that our matching worked.

89
00:04:50,510 --> 00:04:53,360
At the top right, you see
the new Kaplan-Meier plot

90
00:04:53,360 --> 00:04:56,240
using only the matched cohort.

91
00:04:56,240 --> 00:04:58,490
Compare it to the original.

92
00:04:58,490 --> 00:05:01,710
The curves are now
nearly overlapping.

93
00:05:01,710 --> 00:05:05,540
There is no longer a large
difference in outcomes.

94
00:05:05,540 --> 00:05:10,310
This is very different from
what we saw before matching.

95
00:05:10,310 --> 00:05:14,690
But also, notice this still
doesn't look like the RCT result

96
00:05:14,690 --> 00:05:17,090
in the center of the figure.

97
00:05:17,090 --> 00:05:19,580
Imatinib showed a clear
benefit in the trial,

98
00:05:19,580 --> 00:05:22,110
and we still don't
see that here.

99
00:05:22,110 --> 00:05:26,030
So while we have addressed
observed confounding,

100
00:05:26,030 --> 00:05:30,920
this shows that unobserved
confounding likely remains.

101
00:05:30,920 --> 00:05:36,860
And that brings us to step
2, which we will cover next.

102
00:05:36,860 --> 00:05:39,650
In step 2, we aim
to do something

103
00:05:39,650 --> 00:05:41,930
that, to our
knowledge, has not been

104
00:05:41,930 --> 00:05:44,450
done before in this setting.

105
00:05:44,450 --> 00:05:47,840
We aim to address unobserved
confounding, which,

106
00:05:47,840 --> 00:05:51,200
by definition, cannot be
corrected directly through

107
00:05:51,200 --> 00:05:54,990
matching or regression, since
you cannot adjust for something

108
00:05:54,990 --> 00:05:57,320
you cannot observe.

109
00:05:57,320 --> 00:06:00,920
Instead, we focus on correcting
the effect of unobserved

110
00:06:00,920 --> 00:06:04,410
confounders, which,
as we saw in step 1,

111
00:06:04,410 --> 00:06:06,960
is that, even after
prognostic matching,

112
00:06:06,960 --> 00:06:10,820
the Kaplan-Meier curve still
suggests no apparent benefit

113
00:06:10,820 --> 00:06:12,590
from imatinib.

114
00:06:12,590 --> 00:06:14,850
That's not because
the drug doesn't work.

115
00:06:14,850 --> 00:06:17,720
It's because unobserved
confounding continues

116
00:06:17,720 --> 00:06:20,690
to distort the signal.

117
00:06:20,690 --> 00:06:23,160
To overcome this,
we use a novel idea.

118
00:06:23,160 --> 00:06:27,470
We artificially amplify the
observed effect of imatinib

119
00:06:27,470 --> 00:06:30,650
to counteract the
downward bias caused

120
00:06:30,650 --> 00:06:33,740
by unobserved confounding.

121
00:06:33,740 --> 00:06:35,720
How do we do that?

122
00:06:35,720 --> 00:06:38,210
We increase the influence
of treated patients

123
00:06:38,210 --> 00:06:41,900
with good outcomes, those who
received imatinib and did not

124
00:06:41,900 --> 00:06:46,910
recur, by assigning them greater
weights during model training.

125
00:06:46,910 --> 00:06:50,270
The model will then try
to make better predictions

126
00:06:50,270 --> 00:06:52,560
for the patients
with a larger weight

127
00:06:52,560 --> 00:06:55,580
since this yields a greater
improvement in the loss

128
00:06:55,580 --> 00:06:57,110
function.

129
00:06:57,110 --> 00:06:59,270
In turn, this will
improve predictions

130
00:06:59,270 --> 00:07:02,870
in a way that pulls the
treatment effect closer

131
00:07:02,870 --> 00:07:05,210
to what we expect from the RCT.

132
00:07:05,210 --> 00:07:08,270
This approach is called
cost-sensitive learning

133
00:07:08,270 --> 00:07:10,640
and is widely used in
machine learning when

134
00:07:10,640 --> 00:07:12,540
working with imbalanced data.

135
00:07:12,540 --> 00:07:18,130
But here, we repurpose it to
correct for confounding bias.

136
00:07:18,130 --> 00:07:20,340
To the best of our
knowledge, this

137
00:07:20,340 --> 00:07:23,070
is the first time
cost-sensitive learning has

138
00:07:23,070 --> 00:07:26,460
been applied in this context.

139
00:07:26,460 --> 00:07:30,510
It's important to emphasize
how we choose the right weight.

140
00:07:30,510 --> 00:07:33,510
We gradually increased
weight until the sensitivity

141
00:07:33,510 --> 00:07:36,690
of the decision tree, tested
on an external data set

142
00:07:36,690 --> 00:07:40,590
from another
institution, reached 90%.

143
00:07:40,590 --> 00:07:42,240
What does this mean?

144
00:07:42,240 --> 00:07:45,180
It means that the tree
now assigns treatment

145
00:07:45,180 --> 00:07:50,640
to at least 90% of patients
who experienced a recurrence.

146
00:07:50,640 --> 00:07:52,710
Why is this important?

147
00:07:52,710 --> 00:07:55,740
Because it ensures
that our model captures

148
00:07:55,740 --> 00:08:00,060
all high-risk patients, even
those whose recurrence might not

149
00:08:00,060 --> 00:08:03,240
have been preventable
by treatment.

150
00:08:03,240 --> 00:08:07,080
This high-sensitivity target
broadens the treatment

151
00:08:07,080 --> 00:08:10,890
assignment, minimizing the
risk of undertreating someone

152
00:08:10,890 --> 00:08:15,060
who truly needs imatinib.

153
00:08:15,060 --> 00:08:19,270
Now that we have completed
the two deconfounding steps,

154
00:08:19,270 --> 00:08:23,400
we are ready to move from
prediction to decision.

155
00:08:23,400 --> 00:08:27,210
We can now estimate the optimal
treatment for a given patient

156
00:08:27,210 --> 00:08:29,940
by comparing their
predicted prognosis

157
00:08:29,940 --> 00:08:33,030
with and without imatinib.

158
00:08:33,030 --> 00:08:36,390
Naturally, we would
choose whichever option

159
00:08:36,390 --> 00:08:39,809
maximizes survival probability.

160
00:08:39,809 --> 00:08:41,940
But there's a problem.

161
00:08:41,940 --> 00:08:43,950
These predictions
are often generated

162
00:08:43,950 --> 00:08:48,180
using black box models,
such as random forests,

163
00:08:48,180 --> 00:08:51,720
and that creates
a major barrier.

164
00:08:51,720 --> 00:08:54,930
Clinicians will not trust
predictions they cannot

165
00:08:54,930 --> 00:09:00,600
understand, so we need a way to
open the black box to understand

166
00:09:00,600 --> 00:09:03,300
what is driving the
model's predictions.

167
00:09:03,300 --> 00:09:06,510
Specifically, we
want to identify

168
00:09:06,510 --> 00:09:10,830
which patient- or tumor-related
characteristics explain

169
00:09:10,830 --> 00:09:15,330
why the model prefers one
treatment over another.

170
00:09:15,330 --> 00:09:19,920
This brings us to Optimal Policy
Trees, or OPTs, such as the one

171
00:09:19,920 --> 00:09:21,140
displayed on this slide.

172
00:09:21,140 --> 00:09:23,820


173
00:09:23,820 --> 00:09:26,770
To assess how well this
decision tree performs,

174
00:09:26,770 --> 00:09:32,220
we tested it in an
independent external cohort.

175
00:09:32,220 --> 00:09:37,380
In the test cohort from Poland,
which included 557 patients,

176
00:09:37,380 --> 00:09:41,040
the decision tree achieved
a sensitivity of 89%

177
00:09:41,040 --> 00:09:44,160
and a specificity of 70%.

178
00:09:44,160 --> 00:09:49,210
In the validation cohort from
Spain, including 411 patients,

179
00:09:49,210 --> 00:09:55,320
the sensitivity was 85%,
and specificity was 57%.

180
00:09:55,320 --> 00:09:58,000
Let's take a moment to
interpret these numbers.

181
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:00,870
Sensitivity is our safety net.

182
00:10:00,870 --> 00:10:03,060
It reflects the
proportion of patients

183
00:10:03,060 --> 00:10:07,020
who recur and are correctly
assigned to treatment.

184
00:10:07,020 --> 00:10:11,400
So a sensitivity of 89%
means we are catching

185
00:10:11,400 --> 00:10:13,620
almost all high-risk patients.

186
00:10:13,620 --> 00:10:18,120
We are not missing
people who need the drug.

187
00:10:18,120 --> 00:10:20,860
But what is more
exciting is specificity.

188
00:10:20,860 --> 00:10:23,320
This is where the gain happens.

189
00:10:23,320 --> 00:10:28,210
A specificity of 70% means that
we correctly spare treatment

190
00:10:28,210 --> 00:10:33,970
in 70% of patients who would
have received it unnecessarily.

191
00:10:33,970 --> 00:10:36,290
So while sensitivity
keeps us safe,

192
00:10:36,290 --> 00:10:42,850
specificity gives us impact
by reducing overtreatment.

193
00:10:42,850 --> 00:10:48,070
This slide concludes part 1 of
the lecture, where our goal was

194
00:10:48,070 --> 00:10:51,170
to identify patients who
do not need treatment,

195
00:10:51,170 --> 00:10:55,780
those with a good prognosis who
do well even without therapy.

196
00:10:55,780 --> 00:10:59,570
To do that responsibly
using real-world data,

197
00:10:59,570 --> 00:11:02,680
we had to solve two
core challenges--

198
00:11:02,680 --> 00:11:05,800
first, correct for
observed confounding,

199
00:11:05,800 --> 00:11:08,720
and, second, address
unobserved confounding,

200
00:11:08,720 --> 00:11:11,800
which is even harder.

201
00:11:11,800 --> 00:11:16,510
This is where road 1 introduces
three key innovations.

202
00:11:16,510 --> 00:11:20,170
First, it applies a novel
prognostic matching technique

203
00:11:20,170 --> 00:11:23,610
that mimics an
RCT-like population.

204
00:11:23,610 --> 00:11:26,550
We select a subset of
the real-world data

205
00:11:26,550 --> 00:11:29,220
in which treated and
untreated patients have

206
00:11:29,220 --> 00:11:31,860
aligned baseline
prognosis, estimated

207
00:11:31,860 --> 00:11:34,560
using a counterfactual model.

208
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:38,610
This lets us emulate the
structure of a trial and address

209
00:11:38,610 --> 00:11:41,370
observed confounding.

210
00:11:41,370 --> 00:11:45,570
Second, we go a step further
and address unobserved

211
00:11:45,570 --> 00:11:48,660
confounding through
cost-sensitive learning,

212
00:11:48,660 --> 00:11:52,840
increasing the weight of treated
patients with good outcomes.

213
00:11:52,840 --> 00:11:56,280
We repurpose sensitivity
and specificity

214
00:11:56,280 --> 00:12:00,750
as tuning targets so that
the model emphasizes safety,

215
00:12:00,750 --> 00:12:04,650
by not missing high-risk
patients, and utility,

216
00:12:04,650 --> 00:12:08,250
by minimizing
unnecessary treatment.

217
00:12:08,250 --> 00:12:10,690
Finally, to make
this actionable,

218
00:12:10,690 --> 00:12:13,890
we use optimal policy trees.

219
00:12:13,890 --> 00:12:18,070
These trees produce clinically
interpretable rules,

220
00:12:18,070 --> 00:12:20,700
not black box
predictions, allowing

221
00:12:20,700 --> 00:12:24,750
us to understand and trust how
treatment recommendations are

222
00:12:24,750 --> 00:12:26,300
made.